<Layout title="vision">
  <Article
    title="vision"
    section="mysticism"
    updated="archive draft"
  >
    <p>
      vision is the experience of inner seeing—images, scenes, or forms that
      arise within the mind but carry a sense of reality beyond imagination.
    </p>

    <p>
      unlike ordinary thought, vision feels given rather than constructed. it
      appears, often with a clarity or intensity that stands apart from everyday
      mental activity.
    </p>

    <p>
      because of this, visions are often interpreted as messages, revelations,
      or encounters with something beyond the personal mind.
    </p>

    <h2>imaginal space</h2>

    <p>
      vision takes place in an imaginal space—not purely external, but not
      entirely subjective either. it exists between perception and thought.
    </p>

    <p>
      this space allows symbols, figures, and environments to appear in a way
      that feels alive rather than invented.
    </p>

    <h2>intensity</h2>

    <p>
      visions often carry a heightened emotional or perceptual intensity. they
      may feel more vivid than ordinary experience, even if they occur inwardly.
    </p>

    <p>
      this intensity contributes to their sense of importance, but it does not
      guarantee truth.
    </p>

    <h2>interpretation</h2>

    <p>
      like synchronicity, vision requires careful interpretation. it can reveal
      something meaningful, but it can also reflect projection, desire, or fear.
    </p>

    <p>
      the task is not to accept or reject immediately, but to stay with the
      image and allow its meaning to unfold over time.
    </p>

